Overview
--------

TEEFS is designed to be an object storage for Global Platform TEE Persistent
Objects for Flash storages. TEEFS is not a general purpose file system
(flat filesystem, no real directories, no links) but it has many typical
filesystem characteristics like:

- API to create, open, seek, read, write, truncate, rename and delete files.
- Journaling support to fall back to last known good state in case of failure.
- Perfect wear leveling for (Flash) storage.
- Bad block management to work its way around bad blocks.
- Support for page level encryption in TEEDEV.

TEEDEV is the device abstraction TEEFS uses to read and save pages to the
physical media. It can be implemented as a small layer using any (Flash)
driver for the real work. A unit test device in `simdev.c` is an example
TEEDEV that simulates Flash/OTP as a file in the development host.

TEEFS supports a configurable number of filesystem instances. Each instance
is bound to a TEEDEV. TEEDEVs need to be registered to a mount point before
TEEFS can make use of them.


Design goals
------------

As noted in previous chapter, TEEFS is designed to be an object storage for
Global Platform TEE Persistent Objects for Flash storages. In addition,
these have been the driving design goals:

- Small memory footprint both in terms of code size and runtime RAM usage.
  TEEFS can work with only one page as a cache at runtime.
- No dynamic memory allocation.
- Ability to create very small filesystems, starting from just few kilobytes.
- Focus on reliability and recoverability.


Important files, functions and structures
-----------------------------------------

TEEFS external API is defined in `include/fs/teefs.h`. Internal definitions are
in `subsys/fs/teefs/src/teeint.h`. Complete implementation is in
`subsys/fs/teefs/src/teefs.c`.

TEEDEV external API is defined in `include/fs/teedev.h`. Simulation device
is implemented in `subsys/fs/teefs/src/simdev.c` and it is used in unit test
`subsys/fs/teefs/src/simfs.c`.

One important function is `teefs_mount` which mounts the filesystem.
It scans the filesystem blocks for the latest root entry. Root entries
serve as journal entries that can be scanned to search for files.

Function `teefs_gc` does garbage collecting which is needed to make room
for new files by 'removing' deleted files.

Finally, `prog_file` serves as a workhorse for all functions that save files,
that is, `teefs_create`, `teefs_write`, `teefs_truncate`, `teefs_rename` and
also `teefs_gc`.

Thread safety
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

All functions are thread safe. Accessing a TEEFS instance simultaneously
from multiple threads/processes is protected if CONFIG_TEEFS_MULTITHREADING
is set.


Operation principles
--------------------

Each page starts with a `tee_page_t` structure telling the page id and type.
Page id is a running counter where the lowest bits tell the physical page.
Page type is either `ROOT` for journal entries or `FILE` for actual files.

Block and page sizes are defined by TEEDEV implementation, for a Flash
device block size equals erase block size and page size equals write size
which is typically smaller.

Every time a file is written TEEFS writes one `ROOT` journal page after
the `FILE` pages. For delete TEEFS just writes a new `ROOT`. Journal pages
serve as the manifest for the files in the filesystem. Because TEEFS is
accessing raw flash pages via TEEDEV, it cannot rewrite a page already
written. Anything written stays there until corresponding block is erased.

When existing file is changed somehow, for example when new data is appended,
TEEFS always rewrites the entire file and the following `ROOT` marks the old
version of the file deleted. Later on when `teefs_gc` is called, it searches
the root chain for deleted entries and can make that space available for new
files.

Write caching
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Depending on the number of cache pages in TEEDEV writes may be buffered.
Even just a few cache pages will typically reduce the number of writes a lot.
However, write buffering also means there's higher chance to lose data in
case of power failure, for example. Only the files before the last valid
`ROOT` are considered valid when TEEFS is mounted!

NOTE: A recovery mount option has not been implemented. It could be,
and with that it would be possible to recover even the files that were
written to the media without the final `ROOT` page.

An example run
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

In the following example we create one file with initial data, then write
some more data into it. Finally we do garbage collecting to free up the
deleted version of the file.

All diagrams below are produced by running `teedump` utility that visualizes
filesystem contents.

This is the state after creating the filesystem, just one empty root page:

----
 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000000  ROOT                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | state:    OK                                         |
 | roots:           1                                   |
 | prev_id:  FFFFFFFF                                   |
 | first_id: 00000000                                   |
 | infos:           0                                   |
 +------------------------------------------------------+
----

Then we created the file which fits into one page and is followed by a
root entry.

----
 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000001  FILE                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876                                   |
 | namelen:         5                                   |
 | datalen:         5                                   |
 | name: 00000000: 66 69 6c 65  31 00 00 00  |file1...| |
 | data: 00000000: 64 61 74 61  31 00 00 00  |data1...| |
 +------------------------------------------------------+

 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000002  ROOT                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | state:    OK                                         |
 | roots:           1                                   |
 | prev_id:  FFFFFFFF                                   |
 | first_id: 00000000                                   |
 | infos:           1                                   |
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876 old_id: 00000000 new_id: 00000001 |
 +------------------------------------------------------+
----

Then we appended some data which makes a new file entry and new root entry:

----
 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000003  FILE                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876                                   |
 | namelen:         5                                   |
 | datalen:        20                                   |
 | name: 00000000: 66 69 6c 65  31 00 00 00  |file1...| |
 | data: 00000000: 64 61 74 61  31 5f 77 69  |data1_wi| |
 +------------------------------------------------------+

 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000004  ROOT                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | state:    OK                                         |
 | roots:           1                                   |
 | prev_id:  FFFFFFFF                                   |
 | first_id: 00000000                                   |
 | infos:           2                                   |
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876 old_id: 00000000 new_id: 00000001 |
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876 old_id: 00000001 new_id: 00000003 |
 +------------------------------------------------------+
----

The root entry above says we have a file with old page id 00000001 and
new page id 00000003. This means we can garbage collect the old file.
Function `teefs_gc` first creates a new clean root entry and starts
moving files from the last root entry:

----
 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000005  ROOT                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | state:    GC                                         |
 | roots:           2                                   |
 | prev_id:  00000004                                   |
 | first_id: 00000005                                   |
 | infos:           0                                   |
 +------------------------------------------------------+

 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000006  FILE                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876                                   |
 | namelen:         5                                   |
 | datalen:        20                                   |
 | name: 00000000: 66 69 6c 65  31 00 00 00  |file1...| |
 | data: 00000000: 64 61 74 61  31 5f 77 69  |data1_wi| |
 +------------------------------------------------------+

 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000007  ROOT                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | state:    GC                                         |
 | roots:           2                                   |
 | prev_id:  00000004                                   |
 | first_id: 00000005                                   |
 | infos:           1                                   |
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876 old_id: 00000003 new_id: 00000006 |
 +------------------------------------------------------+

 +------------------------------------------------------+
 | 00000008  ROOT                                       |
 |------------------------------------------------------|
 | state:    OK                                         |
 | roots:           1                                   |
 | prev_id:  00000004                                   |
 | first_id: 00000005                                   |
 | infos:           1                                   |
 | fnv_hash: 80E7A876 old_id: 00000003 new_id: 00000006 |
 +------------------------------------------------------+
----

Finally TEEFS state is set back to OK and a final root is written.
Notice that `first_id` in the root entry has value 00000005 which is the
first page actually in use. Pages 00000000 - 00000004 are now available
for new data once we wrap around to the first block again.

In this case there was only one file to move, but typically there are many
and garbage collecting will move the live files over the deleted ones.

Setting more than one cache page for a TEEDEV will reduce the number of
intermediate root entries and write buffering may also mean that intermediate
file updates are not written to the media.


TEEFS configuration
-------------------

----
config TEEFS_MAX_INSTANCES
	int "Max number of TEEFS instances"
	depends on TEEFS
	default 1
	help
	  Defines the maximum number of TEEFS instances. One instance is
	  connected to one device and operates individually. A device is
	  connected to a mount point and needs to be there before TEEFS
	  functions will work.

config TEEFS_MAX_PAGES
	int "Max number of pages in log2"
	depends on TEEFS
	default 15
	help
	  Valid values are 31, 15 and 7 in log2.
	  With value 31 TEEFS can have 1 << 31 pages in a filesystem.
	  With value 15 TEEFS can have 1 << 15 pages in a filesystem.
	  With value 7 TEEFS can have 1 << 7 pages in a filesystem.
	  The smaller the value the more space is saved on each page header.
	  This may have a meaning in small OTP filesystems, for example,
	  where each byte counts. Note that this is common setting for all
	  teefs instances. Select the value depending on your use and your
	  devices.

config TEEFS_MAX_FILES
	int "Max number of TEEFS file descriptors"
	depends on TEEFS
	default 8
	help
	  Defines the maximum number of TEEFS pre-allocated file descriptors.
	  This means the maximum number of open files at once for all TEEFS
	  instances. File descriptors do not take much memory.

config TEEFS_MAX_DIRS
	int "Max number of TEEFS directory descriptors"
	depends on TEEFS
	default 1
	help
	  Defines the maximum number of pre-allocated TEEFS directory
	  descriptors. This means the maximum number of open directories
	  at once for all TEEFS instances. Directory descriptors are more
	  costly in terms of memory usage.

config TEEFS_MAX_PAGE_SIZE
	int "Max supported page size in log2"
	depends on TEEFS
	default 8
	help
	  Maximum supported page size. This should be tuned to match the
	  largest device page size configuration. TEEFS allocates data
	  structures based on this value.

config TEEFS_MAX_CACHE_PAGES
	int "Max supported number of pages to keep in cache"
	depends on TEEFS
	default 4
	help
	  TEEFS works fine with just one cache page. If there's more memory
	  to spare this can be set larger to reduce the need to read/write
	  pages from/to the disk device. This should be tuned to match the
	  largest device cache pages configuration.

config TEEFS_MAX_BAD_BLOCKS
	int "Reserve for possible bad blocks"
	depends on CMRT_TEEDEV_DMAC
	default 1
	help
	  Blocks reserved to go around possible contiguous bad blocks.

config TEEFS_MAX_NAMELEN
	int "Maximum length reserved for file names"
	depends on TEEFS
	range 1 255
	default 64
	help
	  Maximum file name length. Default value is 64 which comes from the
	  TEE specification. File name will be truncated if first page cannot
	  fit maximum file name length. This setting should be tuned to fit
	  the smallest filesystem, like an OTP filesystem, where there is
	  no space to spare.

config TEEFS_MULTITHREADING
	bool
	prompt "TEEFS multithreading support"
	default y if CONFIG_MULTITHREADING
	default n
	help
	  Enable multithreading support in the TEEFS filesystem.
----

Typical TEEDEV configuration
----------------------------

Include `fs/teedev.h` with these defines to create a RAM device and allocate
static memory structures for it:

----
#define TEEDEV_BLOCK_SIZE 12 /* erase block size in log2 (1 << value) */
#define TEEDEV_PAGE_SIZE 8 /* page size in log2 (1 << value) */
#define TEEDEV_CACHE_PAGES 4 /* nr of cache pages, see TEEFS_MAX_CACHE_PAGES */
#define TEEDEV_WRITE_ONCE false /* true for OTP, false for FLASH/RAM/etc. */
#define TEEDEV_WRITE_OVER false /* true for OTP/RAM/etc., false for FLASH. */
#define TEEDEV_AUTO_OBLITERATE false /* can be true if write_over is allowed */
#undef TEEDEV_CRYPTO /* define to use encrypted FS */
#define TEEDEV_RAM /* define to use in-built RAM device */
#include <fs/teedev.h>
#include <fs/teefs.h>
----

Adding new device
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

If there's need for new devices in addition to TEEDEV_RAM, TEEDEV_DMAC,
TEEDEV_FLASH and TEEDEV_OTP, one needs to add the calls into `fs/teedev.h`
and the implementation into `drivers/cmrt/teefs/`.


Simulation and unit testing
---------------------------

The `Makefile` will build two binaries you can run in your development host,
a `teesim` for running `src/simfs.c` and `teedump` which can be used to
visualize filesystem contents.

Currently `src/simfs.c` just calls a bunch of TEEFS API functions and finally
verifies that filesystem state is correct. The filesystem is simulated as a
file `teesim.bin` in your development host.

The best tool for testing the filesystem itself is `src/stressit.c` which
runs TEEFS operations side by side with the development host filesystem
and makes sure they have the same contents.
